values:
I'm going home. I'm tempted to stay home, but that's just because home seems better than it is right now. I think I've developed an allergy to the whole east coast. Maybe just to most the places I've ever been.

I have a perspective problem--either too much or not enough, or both. I can see til tonight and til next summer, but not next week, so next week is just this irritating thing keeping me from the real future. And I don't have the emotional energy to be around anyone or motivate myself. I definitely don't have the energy to deal with my lack of energy or perspective.

I do have the energy to go home, so that's what I'm doing.
The buildings in Harlem along the Henry Hudson Parkway are covered in kudzu that is turning colors with the fall. It is one of the most beautiful things I have ever seen.

Nothing like a brilliant life followed by a young death to make everything that matters seem real and everything everyone bitches about seem absurd.

Love to C-Feld, always, always, always.

This has been the happiest and most successful night of my semester.

Love love love life. Afraid of expectations. But love life.
Love you, miss you, wish I could be there.

First kiss and the first time that I felt connected to anything

And than the second boot falls.
And then a third, a fourth, a fifth.

Ahh life is so wonderfully weird right now. I'm really together. I'm solid enough to be doing things as experiments and seeing what happens to me. That sounds really gross but I promise it's not. This is why: I was operating under the assumption that I don't trust myself, because it seemed safer to question everything, myself included. I've been operating like that for years. Always be sure, always guarantee results.

Turns out, I do trust myself! Fucking loads. Cool, yeah?

One year ago, we were in the midst of Twelfth Night hell week. Last November, I made this post during Inherit hell week. My first college hell week starts tomorrow.

Go back and look at that post. What I want to know is this:

How have you changed since you commented anonymously almost a year ago? Do you even remember which response is yours? Is whatever you wrote still "one true thing?" Don't let a lack of response then stop you from responding now, either, if you want to. What has the past year meant for your identity?

Anon-comments are enabled (and encouraged).

The act of stopping several times a day to observe what you’re feeling or thinking can become, after weeks and weeks, a sort of philosophical act. It’s like the Greek dictum to “know thyself,” or the therapeutic concept of mindfulness. (Indeed, the question that floats eternally at the top of Twitter’s Web site — “What are you doing?” — can come to seem existentially freighted. What are you doing?) Having an audience can make the self-reflection even more acute, since, as my interviewees noted, they’re trying to describe their activities in a way that is not only accurate but also interesting to others: the status update as a literary form.
